INSERT INTO units (phase_id, sort_order, title, reading, lesson, field_drill, debrief_prompt, is_exam, exam_questions) VALUES
(2,1,'Ch.1-5: Types of States & How to Hold Them','The Prince, Chapters 1-5 (short chapters)','New acquisitions are hard to hold; people accept new rulers hoping for better, then revolt when disappointed. Key: whoever causes another to become powerful ruins himself. Also: live there yourself (be present in what you rule) - problems seen early are cured easily, seen late are incurable.','Audit one domain of your life you "conquered" then abandoned (a habit, a skill, a system that decayed). Re-occupy it: schedule 15 minutes of presence in it daily this week.','What problem did I catch early today? What problem am I currently letting grow because I refuse to look at it?',0,NULL),
(2,2,'Ch.6-9: Virtù vs Fortuna - The Four Paths to Power','The Prince, Chapters 6-9','Four paths: own ability (virtù), luck (fortuna), crime, or others'' favor. Those who rise by virtù gain hard but hold easily; those who rise by fortune gain easily but hold hard. THE core concept: build skills and systems so thoroughly that luck matters less. Fortune is a river - you cannot stop the flood, but you build dikes in calm weather.','List 3 things in your life currently depending on luck (hoping the exam is easy, hoping motivation shows up, hoping money lasts). For ONE of them, build a dike today: a preparation that makes luck irrelevant.','Where did I rely on fortuna today when virtù was available?',0,NULL),
(2,3,'Ch.10-14: Arms and Foundations','The Prince, Chapters 10-14','The chief foundations of all states are good laws and good arms. Mercenaries are useless and dangerous - never outsource your core power. A prince must study war constantly, in peace even more than in war. Applied: your skills are your army. Never delegate your foundation. Study your craft daily like your survival depends on it - it does.','Name your "mercenaries": what core capability are you renting instead of owning (copying answers, AI-dependence without understanding, borrowed discipline from apps)? Pick one and train the in-house version for 30 minutes today.','Did I train my army today, or did I hire mercenaries?',0,NULL),
(2,4,'Ch.15-16: The Effectual Truth','The Prince, Chapters 15-16','THE revolutionary chapter. "He who neglects what IS done for what OUGHT to be done effects his ruin." See the world as it is, not as churchmen say it should be. A prince must learn how NOT to be good - and use it or not according to necessity. Generosity performed for reputation bankrupts you; strategic "meanness" funds real strength.','Reality audit: write down one situation where you are currently acting on how things SHOULD be (people should notice my work, effort should be rewarded, friends should reciprocate) instead of how they ARE. Rewrite your strategy for the real world.','Where did I confuse "ought" with "is" today?',0,NULL),
(2,5,'Ch.17-18: Feared vs Loved, The Lion and The Fox','The Prince, Chapters 17-18','Better to be feared than loved IF you must choose - because love depends on THEIR obligation, fear on YOUR action. But the absolute constraint: NEVER be hated. And Ch.18: the fox recognizes traps, the lion frightens wolves. Everyone sees what you appear to be, few feel what you are. MASTER READING: this is about respect and boundaries, not cruelty - be someone whose standards are feared (taken seriously), whose reactions are predictable, and who is never caught manipulating.','Boundary drill: identify one place people currently take you lightly (missed commitments to you, your time disrespected). Set ONE clear, calm boundary this week - stated once, enforced without anger.','Was I the fox today (saw the traps)? Was I the lion (taken seriously)? Was I neither?',0,NULL),
(2,6,'Ch.19-21: Avoiding Hatred, Earning Reputation','The Prince, Chapters 19-21','A prince must avoid being hated or despised above ALL - hatred is the one force that finds a way through every defense. Despised = seen as fickle, frivolous, effeminate, irresolute. Be the opposite: greatness, courage, gravity, strength in your actions. Nothing wins esteem like great enterprises: take clear positions, finish visible things.','Reputation audit: what have you publicly started and not finished? Choose one visible unfinished thing and either finish it this week or formally close it. Irresolution is how respect dies.','Did anything I did today make me look fickle or irresolute to anyone - including to myself?',0,NULL),
(2,7,'Ch.22-23: Counselors and Flatterers','The Prince, Chapters 22-23','A ruler''s brain is judged by the people around him. Flattery is a plague - the only defense is making truth-telling safe (but only when YOU ask). Choose advisors who think of YOUR interests, not theirs. Applied: audit your circle - who tells you the truth? Who only agrees?','Circle audit: write your 5 most-consulted people (including online voices). Mark each T (tells me truths I dislike) or F (flatters/agrees). If you have fewer than 2 T''s, actively ask one honest person this week: "What am I doing wrong that I cannot see?"','Who lied to me pleasantly today - and did I reward them for it?',0,NULL),
(2,8,'Ch.24-26: Fortune''s River and The Call','The Prince, Chapters 24-26','Fortune controls half our actions but leaves the other half to us. Fortune is a woman/river: favors the bold and the adaptive, destroys the rigid. The failed princes of Italy blamed fortune - Machiavelli says: your habits did not change when the times changed. THE final lesson: adapt or die. When circumstances shift, the man who cannot change his nature is broken by them.','Adaptation audit: what changed in your circumstances in the last year (new semester, new responsibilities, new environment) that your HABITS have not yet adapted to? Design the adapted habit today.','What changed around me recently that I am still responding to with old strategies?',0,NULL),
(2,9,'INTEGRATION EXAM - The Prince','Review all chapters + drill reports + maxim bank','Prove the cold anthropology is installed - as strategic clarity, not paranoia.','The exam is the drill. Brutal self-grading. Naive readings = automatic fail.',NULL,1,'["Define virtù vs fortuna in your own words and give one dike you actually built during this phase.","State the effectual truth doctrine (Ch.15) and one real example where you replaced ought with is.","Feared vs loved: explain the MASTER reading (not the naive one) and describe the boundary you set in unit 5 - did it hold?","Why is never be hated the constraint that governs all other tactics? What happens to detected manipulators over time (use the reputation-network argument)?","The lion and the fox: give one trap you RECOGNIZED this month (fox) and one moment you were taken seriously because of standards, not aggression (lion).","Circle audit results: who are your T''s? What uncomfortable truth did you extract in unit 7?","Ch.24-26: what did you adapt? What would Machiavelli say is your current rigidity most likely to be punished by fortune?","FINAL: Explain in 4 sentences why The Prince read WRONG produces paranoid manipulators, and what the correct extraction is. (You wrote the answer with your own life this phase - use it.)"]');
INSERT INTO units (phase_id, sort_order, title, reading, lesson, field_drill, debrief_prompt, is_exam, exam_questions) VALUES
(3,1,'Book 1 (selections): Republics and the People','Discourses on Livy, Book 1, Ch.1-12 (read slowly - dense)','The OTHER Machiavelli: the people are wiser and more constant than princes. Good orders (institutions/systems) make good fortune. Conflict between classes, managed by law, made Rome strong - friction channeled by structure creates power, not weakness. Your takeaway: build ORDERS (routines, laws, reviews) that outlive your moods.','Constitution drill: your 7 Laws are your republic''s constitution. Tonight, review each law and write one sentence on whether your "orders" held this month or whether you ruled by mood (like a weak prince).','Did my systems govern me today, or did my moods stage a coup?',0,NULL),
(3,2,'Book 1 (selections): Corruption and Renewal','Discourses Book 1, Ch.16-18 + Book 3, Ch.1','States decay unless periodically brought back to their beginnings. Renewal requires returning to founding principles - shock the system back to its origins before corruption completes. Applied: routines decay silently. Scheduled resets (weekly review, monthly re-read of your laws) are not optional maintenance, they ARE the system.','Renewal drill: re-read your original reasons for starting this whole program (your first debriefs). Write what has silently decayed since day 1 and perform one renewal act today.','What founding principle of mine has quietly corrupted - and when did I stop noticing?',0,NULL),
(3,3,'Book 2-3 (selections): Expansion and Captains','Discourses Book 2 Ch.1-2, Book 3 Ch.9, 31','Rome expanded through virtù and adaptive institutions. Book 3 Ch.9: he errs who believes he can succeed with the same conduct in all times - Fabius'' caution won one war and would have lost another. Great captains match method to moment. Also: strong men remain the same in all fortunes - dignity in victory AND defeat.','Method-matching drill: identify one area where your current method worked BEFORE but is failing NOW (study technique, social approach, work style). Consciously switch methods this week and log results.','Was today a Fabius day (patience) or a Scipio day (boldness)? Did I match the method to the moment?',0,NULL),
(3,4,'INTEGRATION EXAM - The Complete Machiavelli','Both books + all your drill reports','The synthesis exam: Prince + Discourses = the whole man. Almost nobody reaches this point. You did.',NULL,NULL,1,'["Explain the apparent contradiction between The Prince and the Discourses, and resolve it (context: 1513 Italy, the Medici, republics vs emergencies).","What are good orders and why does Machiavelli trust them over good men? Give YOUR two strongest orders and the evidence they work.","Return to beginnings: what did your renewal drill uncover, and what renewal ritual will you keep permanently?","Match the method to the moment: give your example from unit 3 and its result.","FINAL SYNTHESIS: Write your own 10-line Machiavelli - ten maxims in YOUR words that you have personally verified with drills. This document is your graduation certificate."]');
INSERT INTO units (phase_id, sort_order, title, reading, lesson, field_drill, debrief_prompt, is_exam, exam_questions) VALUES
(4,1,'Greene: 48 Laws of Power (selections I)','Laws 1-16 (read as commentary on what you already mastered)','NOW you can read Greene safely - you have the originals as your immune system. Read each law asking: which Sun Tzu or Machiavelli principle is this amplifying? Which laws are observation tools (defense) vs manipulation tools (avoid)?','For 5 laws of your choice, write the source principle (Sun Tzu or Machiavelli chapter) it derives from, and mark each: DEFENSE (recognize when used on me) or AVOID.','Did I catch anyone using a Greene law on me today?',0,NULL),
(4,2,'Greene: 48 Laws of Power (selections II)','Laws 17-33','Continue the mapping. Special attention: Law 15 (crush your enemy totally) and similar - these are the laws that read naively destroy people. Write the master reading for each dangerous law.','Pick the 3 most dangerous laws in this batch and write their master readings (what the wise extraction is vs the cartoon version).','Which law tempted me with its naive reading today?',0,NULL),
(4,3,'Musashi: The Book of Five Rings','Full book (it is short) - Ground, Water, Fire, Wind, Void','The lone warrior''s Sun Tzu. Key: the Way is in training - you can only fight the way you practice. Do nothing which is of no use. Perceive that which cannot be seen by the eye. Musashi is about DEPTH in your single craft - 60 duels won by more preparation, not more talent.','Musashi audit: list everything you did yesterday and mark each item useful or of-no-use (his standard, not comfort''s standard). Cut ONE useless recurring thing permanently.','Did I train today the way I intend to fight?',0,NULL),
(4,4,'Clausewitz: On War (selections)','Book 1 Ch.1, Book 3 (friction chapters) - selections only','Two immortal concepts: FRICTION (everything in war is simple, but the simplest thing is difficult - plans degrade on contact with reality) and the CULMINATING POINT (every offensive weakens as it advances; know when to stop). Applied: build slack into plans; recognize when pushing further destroys gains.','Friction log: today, write down every small friction that degraded your plan (lost keys, slow wifi, unexpected call). Then redesign tomorrow with 20% buffer capacity for friction.','Did I hit a culminating point today - a moment where continuing made things worse - and did I recognize it?',0,NULL),
(4,5,'GRAND FINAL EXAM - The Strategist','Everything. All phases, all drill reports, your full maxim bank.','The final integration. You are no longer reading strategy - you think in it.',NULL,NULL,1,'["A friend is being manipulated by someone at university. Using named principles from at least 3 different books, write the counter-strategy you would design for them.","You have 3 weeks to prepare for your hardest exam ever. Design the full campaign using the Five Factors, terrain mapping, spies, dikes against fortune, and friction buffers - all named.","Someone insults you publicly. Write the responses of: naive Greene reader, paranoid Machiavelli misreader, and YOU (the master reading). Explain why yours wins long-term.","Define in your own words: virtù, formlessness, culminating point, good orders, the effectual truth, never miss twice. One sentence each - compression proves mastery.","FINAL: Write the one-page constitution of your next 5 years: your laws, your orders, your renewal rituals, your terrain. This is the document the whole campaign existed to produce."]');
INSERT INTO units (phase_id, sort_order, title, reading, lesson, field_drill, debrief_prompt, is_exam, exam_questions) VALUES
(5,1,'Marcus Aurelius: Meditations (Books 1-6)','Meditations, Books 1-6 - slow, pen in hand, ~10 pages/night','A Roman emperor''s private journal - he was doing YOUR nightly debrief 1,900 years ago. Core: you control your judgments, not events. The obstacle is the way. Waste no more time arguing what a good man should be - be one.','Each night this unit, before your debrief, apply ONE Marcus line to something that irritated you today. Rewrite the event through his lens.','What did I judge today that I could have simply observed?',0,NULL),
(5,2,'Marcus Aurelius: Meditations (Books 7-12)','Meditations, Books 7-12','The deeper books: impermanence, the view from above, doing your duty without needing applause. The art of acquiescence paired with relentless action - accept what happened, act on what is next.','View-from-above drill: once this unit, when stressed, mentally zoom out (your room -> your city -> the planet -> 100 years from now). Write what the stress looked like from up there.','Did I need applause today? What did I do that was complete in itself without it?',0,NULL),
(5,3,'Epictetus: Enchiridion','The Enchiridion (very short - read twice during this unit)','The dichotomy of control, weaponized. Some things are up to us (judgments, impulses, desires), some are not (body, reputation, others'' actions). ALL suffering comes from confusing the two. It is not events that disturb us, but our opinions about events.','Control audit: take your 3 current biggest worries. Split each into the part up to you / not up to you. Act on the first column TODAY, formally release the second in writing.','Which column did I live in today?',0,NULL),
(5,4,'Seneca: Letters from a Stoic (selections)','Letters 1, 2, 5, 13, 16, 18, 26, 49, 78, 83','The practical Stoic. Letter 1: on saving time - we are not given a short life, we make it short. Letter 13: we suffer more in imagination than reality. Letter 18: practice poverty - rehearse hardship so fortune cannot ambush you.','Seneca''s rehearsal: pick one comfort and remove it for 48 hours (phone at dinner, sugar, music while working). Observe: was the hardship real or imagined?','What did I suffer today in imagination that never arrived in reality?',0,NULL),
(5,5,'Plato: The Apology + Crito','Both dialogues (short)','Socrates on trial: the unexamined life is not worth living. He dies rather than abandon his principles - the ultimate never be despised. Crito: it is never right to do wrong, even in return for wrong. Foundation stone of Western integrity.','Examination drill: Socratic-question ONE of your own strong opinions this week: What do I actually mean? How do I know? What would change my mind? Write the exchange.','What belief did I carry today that I have never actually examined?',0,NULL),
(5,6,'Plato: The Republic (Books 1-4, selections)','Republic selections: the Ring of Gyges, the tripartite soul, justice as inner order','The Ring of Gyges: would you be just if you could never be caught? (This is the direct answer to naive Machiavellianism.) The soul has three parts - reason, spirit, appetite - and justice is reason ruling. Your discipline program IS Plato''s inner republic.','Gyges drill: identify one thing you do correctly ONLY because someone might see. Do it correctly once this week when absolutely no one can know. Note how it felt.','Which part ruled my soul today: reason, spirit, or appetite?',0,NULL),
(5,7,'Nietzsche: Thus Spoke Zarathustra (Part 1)','Zarathustra, Prologue + Part 1 (slow - it is poetry)','The three metamorphoses: camel (carry the heavy load - your discipline phase), lion (say sacred No to imposed values), child (create your own). You are currently becoming the camel ON PURPOSE - that is the difference between discipline and slavery.','Metamorphosis audit: list your current loads. Mark each: chosen (camel by choice) or imposed (camel by default). For one imposed load, decide: transform it into chosen, or lion-No it.','Was I camel, lion, or child today - and was it by choice?',0,NULL),
(5,8,'Nietzsche: Beyond Good and Evil (selections)','BGE: Preface, Part 1 (On the Prejudices of Philosophers), Part 4 (aphorisms)','Question even your questioners. Will to power as self-overcoming: the discipline you have built is not restriction - it is your will giving itself LAW. He who cannot obey himself will be commanded. You built this app so you command yourself.','Self-overcoming log: name one former limit of yours that this entire program has already broken. Then name the next one on the list.','What commanded me today: my law or my impulse?',0,NULL),
(5,9,'PHILOSOPHY INTEGRATION EXAM - The Examined Life','All philosophy units + your drill reports',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'["State the dichotomy of control and give the real example from your unit 3 audit - what did you release and did it stay released?","The Ring of Gyges vs naive Machiavellianism: connect them. Why is the person who is just only when watched strategically WEAK (use reputation-network logic)?","Marcus vs Nietzsche: one says accept, one says overcome. Resolve the contradiction using your own daily routine as the example.","Which single philosophical practice changed your actual behavior most? Evidence from your debriefs required.","FINAL: The unexamined life is not worth living. You now have months of nightly examinations logged. Read your first 5 debriefs and your last 5. Write one page: who was that person, who is this one?"]');
